{{Use Australian English|date=January 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}} {{Infobox person | name = Franco Belgiorno-Nettis {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AC|CBE}} | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1915|06|20|df=y}} | birth_place = Italy | death_date = {{Death date and age|2006|07|08|1915|06|20|df=y}} | occupation = Businessman | nationality = Australian | years_active = | religion = | height = 1.57 m | parents = | siblings = | children = Marco, Luca and Guido<ref>{{citation |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Commission |url=http://www.abc.net.au/dynasties/txt/s982538.htm |title=Belgiorno-Nettis |work= Dynasties |date=15 December 2003}}</ref><ref name=NPG/> | partner = Amina Belgiorno-Nettis }}
'''Franco Belgiorno-Nettis''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AC|CBE}} (20 June 1915 – 8 July 2006) was an [[Australia]]n industrialist and patron of the arts. He founded the construction and engineering company [[Transfield]] and also helped establish the Australian Biennale subsequently known as the [[Biennale of Sydney]].<ref name=NPG/><ref name=Stephens/>
==Biography== Belgiorno-Nettis was born in [[Cassano delle Murge]] in the [[Province of Bari]] in [[Apulia]], [[Italy]] in 1915 and attended the Turin Military Academy before joining the Italian army and serving in [[North Africa]] during [[World War II]].<ref name=Stephens>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/obituaries/an-achiever-whose-dreams-came-true/2006/07/10/1152383674252.html?page=fullpage#contentSwap1 |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |publisher=Fairfax Media |date=11 July 2006 |title=An achiever whose dreams came true |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109012742/http://www.smh.com.au/news/obituaries/an-achiever-whose-dreams-came-true/2006/07/10/1152383674252.html?page=fullpage |archivedate=9 January 2016 |first=Tony |last=Stephens}}</ref> He spent 3 years at an allied [[Prisoner-of-war camp|POW camp]] in [[India]]. After the war he returned to Italy to complete his studies in engineering at the [[University of Turin]]. In 1951 he came to Australia as the employee of Italian engineering firm Electric Power Transmission, (an offshoot of Milan-based Societa' Anonima Elettrificazione), which was constructing powerlines.
Franco Belgiorno-Nettis and Amina Cerino-Zegna wed by proxy in 1951 &ndash; Belgiorno-Nettis' brother represented him at the altar of Turin Cathedral for the marriage. Amina soon after joined her husband in Australia, and their three sons, Marco Belgiorno-Zegna, Luca Belgiorno-Nettis and Guido Belgiorno-Nettis, were born between 1953 and 1959.<ref name=NPG>{{cite web |url= http://www.portrait.gov.au/people/amina-belgiorno-nettis |publisher= National Portrait Gallery |title= Amina Belgiorno-Nettis}}</ref>
In 1956 he and his professional partner, [[Carlo Salteri]], set up [[Transfield Services|Transfield]] which became the largest construction and engineering firm in the [[Southern Hemisphere]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/the-deal-magazine/transfields-luca-belgiornonettis-branches-into-information-technology/news-story/be2114283dbc9ec64ac853687425d933 |newspaper=The Australian |date=15 May 2015 |title=Transfield’s Luca Belgiorno-Nettis branches into information technology |first=Tom |last=Dusevic |publisher=News Corp}}</ref>
He was also prominent as a patron of the arts. In 1961 he set up the [[Transfield Art Prize]].<ref name=Stephens/> He also helped to found the [[Biennale of Sydney]] in 1973.
Franco Belgiorno-Nettis died in 2006 aged 91 either after a fall while on holiday in Italy,<ref name=Stephens/> and/or of a terminal brain stroke while attending to home maintenance in Italy.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}
==Recognition== *In 1976 he was appointed a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) for contributions to the arts.<ref name=CBE>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1065135&search_type=simple&showInd=true The Order of the British Empire - Commander (Civil)] (CBE), 31 December 1976, www.itsanhonour.gov.au</ref> *In 1985 he was appointed a [[Member of the Order of Australia]] (AM) for service to Secondary Industry and to the arts.<ref name=AM>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=870811&search_type=simple&showInd=true Member of the Order of Australia] (AM), 10 June 1985, www.itsanhonour.gov.au</ref> *In 1997 he was appointed a [[Companion of the Order of Australia]] (AC) in recognition of service to the arts, to Australian business through the engineering and construction industry and to the community.<ref name=AC>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=870196&search_type=simple&showInd=true Companion of the Order of Australia] (AC), 26 January 1997, www.itsanhonour.gov.au</ref> *In 2001 he was awarded the [[Centenary Medal]] for service to Australian society in engineering and management,<ref name=CM>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1126960&search_type=simple&showInd=true Centenary Medal], 1 January 2001, www.itsanhonour.gov.au</ref>
His portrait was among the [[2004 Archibald Prize finalists]].([https://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/media/prize_images/Bergstrom-capt2.jpg Copyright image])<ref>[https://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/prizes/archibald/2004/27917/ Franco Belgiorno-Nettis - 'larger than life'] by Danelle Bergstrom, 2004 Archibald Prize finalist, Art Gallery of NSW.</ref>
