{{Infobox non-profit | name = High Five | image = Columbus High Five Logo 2.svg | image_size = 160px | type = | founded_date = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | tax_id = | registration_id = | founder = John Angelo | location = [[Columbus, OH]] | coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|display=inline,title}} --> | origins = | key_people = Diesha Condon | area_served = | product = | mission = | focus = | method = | revenue = | endowment = | num_volunteers = | num_employees = | num_members = | subsid = | opponents = | owner = | non-profit_slogan = | former name = | homepage = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | dissolved = | footnotes = }}
[[Image:Highstreetgraphic.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Map of High Five]] '''High Five''' was a 2010 marketing effort to create a national identity for [[Columbus, Ohio]] by linking the five most distinct districts along {{convert|5|mi}} of historic High Street.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dispatch.com/live/content/business/stories/2010/02/23/city-marketing-plan-is-a-high-five.html | title=City marketing plan is a High Five | work=The Columbus Dispatch | date=February 23, 2010 | accessdate=July 3, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.columbusunderground.com/columbus-high-five-campaign-to-launch-next-week | title=Columbus High Five Campaign to Launch Next Week | publisher=Columbus Underground | date=February 19, 2010 | accessdate=July 3, 2012}}</ref>
== Districts ==
===University District=== {{Main|University District, Columbus, Ohio}} [[The Ohio State University]] has one of the largest campuses in the nation. With over 50,000 students in Columbus alone, the district provides countless sporting events, festivals, concerts and a vibrant night life.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}} [[File:CampusGateway.JPG|thumb|left|South Campus Gateway]]
===Short North=== [[File:ShortNorthArches.jpg|thumb|upright|Arches stretch the street in the Short North]] {{main|The Short North}} The Short North is an unrivalled collection of galleries, restaurants, and boutiques at the artistic heart of [[Ohio]]. With famous arches lining the street, this district provides everything from historic architecture and creative art, to a bohemian setting to enjoy shopping and dining in what is labelled as a "must see" destination by many travel magazines.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}
===Arena District=== {{main|Arena District}} The Arena District is a {{convert|75|acre|km2|abbr=on}} development project that is home to numerous housing and dining options, along with one-of-a-kind concert and sporting venues.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}} With a large presence of [[Nationwide Mutual Insurance Company|Nationwide Insurance]], the district hosts the [[Columbus Blue Jackets]] at [[Nationwide Arena]] and the [[Columbus Clippers]] at [[Huntington Park (Columbus, Ohio)|Huntington Park]].
===Downtown=== {{main|Downtown Columbus, Ohio}} Home to the [[Ohio Statehouse]], downtown produces a mix of business and pleasure. Headquarters of multiple industries are located here, including Huntington Bank and Nationwide Insurance. Parks such as Columbus Commons and the Scioto Mile provide a daily refuge while historic theaters are within walking distance.
===German Village=== {{main|German Village}} German Village is a historic neighborhood south of [[Downtown Columbus, Columbus, Ohio|Downtown Columbus]]. With a number of signature shops and destinations, this area adds a small town feel to an otherwise urban space.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}} [[File:Schiller Park5.jpg|thumb|[[Schiller Park, Columbus, Ohio|Schiller Park]]]]
