{{Use Pakistani English|date=February 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}
'''Saddar''' ({{lang-ur|''' صدر '''}}) is a neighbourhood in [[Saddar Town]] in [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]].<ref>[http://www.karachicity.gov.pk/town/index.asp?txtTown=Saddar Saddar Town – Government of Karachi] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060613010729/http://karachicity.gov.pk/town/index.asp?txtTown=Saddar |date=2006-06-13 }}</ref> The neighbourhood serves as a major commercial centre in the historic British-era core of Karachi. The neighbourhood contains Karachi’s largest concentration of colonial-era architecture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thepeninsulaqatar.com/article/01/03/2018/Pakistan-s-crumbling-architectural-heritage|title=Pakistan's crumbling architectural heritage - The Peninsula Qatar|website=www.thepeninsulaqatar.com|access-date=2018-03-09}}</ref>
==Central business district==
Saddar is the [[central business district]] of Karachi. 'Saddar' generally means 'centre' (of the town) and also 'head' (of State or organization). [[Empress Market]] in Saddar is the central shopping area of [[Karachi]].<ref name=Dawn2>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/742156|author=Nadir Siddiqui|title=Karachi Time Machine|date=2 March 2014|publisher=Dawn (newspaper)|accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref>
Karachi's central bus station ''Regal Bus Stop'' is also located in Saddar, thus connecting it with other areas of [[Karachi]]. A major street in Saddar is named [[Zaibunnisa Street]], after the influential author and journalist, [[Zaib-un-Nissa Hamidullah]]. This street is one of the most modern and bustling in Karachi. Saddar is the hub of business activities in Karachi and is one of the oldest parts of the city. Many beautiful examples of British Colonial architecture can be found here; like the main building of [[Karachi Grammar School]], [[Frere Hall]] and the [[Sindh Club]]. This was the centre of [[Karachi]] in the colonial era, and still is today.
Saddar also has the famous Karachi building called [[Rainbow Centre Karachi|Rainbow Centre]].
There are several ethnic groups in Saddar including [[Muhajir (Pakistan)|Muhajirs]], [[Sindhi people|Sindhis]], [[Punjabi people|Punjabis]], [[Kashmiri people|Kashmiris]], [[Saraiki people|Seraikis]], [[Pashtun people|Pakhtuns]], [[Baloch people|Balochis]], [[Brahui people|Brahuis]], [[Memon people|Memons]], [[Musta'li|Bohras]], [[Ismaili people|Ismailis]], etc. Over 85% of the population is [[Muslim]]. There are also [[Christian]], [[Hindu]], [[Zoroastrian|Parsis]], [[Ahmadis]], and other religious communities in Saddar. The population of [[Saddar Town]] is estimated to be nearly one million.
== Main areas == * Rao Sheraz Khan * Preedy Quarters * Ratan Talao (Partial) (Muslim Public School, Saddar Branch ) * [[Urdu Bazaar (Karachi)|Urdu Bazaar Area]]<ref name=Dawn>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1178911|title=Bookless in Saddar: An adventure through time and traffic|author=Muhammad Umar|publisher=Dawn (newspaper)|date=1 May 2015|accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> * Rainbow Centre * Jehangir Park (A six-acre park donated to the people of Karachi in 1893 by a Parsi philanthropist, Behramjee Jehangirjee Rajkotwala) (recent park renovation completed in 2017)<ref name=Dawn1>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1178911|title=Back to life, historical Jahangir Park awaits formal reopening|author=Imran Ayub|date=15 August 2017|publisher=Dawn (newspaper)|accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> * Gari Khata * Burns Road (Partial) * [[Bohri Bazaar]] (one of the oldest marketplaces of Karachi)<ref name=Dawn3>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/602645|title=Bohri bazaar: Stepping back in time|author=Dawn.com|date=30 January 2011|publisher=Dawn (newspaper)|accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> * Lucky Star * Aram Bagh (Partial) * Passport Office * National Accountability Bureau (Investigation Wing) * [[Sindh High Court]] Building
